Hello,
Up for Auction is a 1986 Ford Mustang SVO. 1986 is the last production year of the SVO Mustang. I have owned the car since 1989. I believe it had a little over 10K miles on it. It has always been garage kept. Never seen rain or snow. The original owner stated that the car never saw rain or snow when I bought it from him. Only Mobil One Synthetic Oil has ever been used. The car has never been in an accident, never needed body repair. The panels are extremely straight and ding-free. There is no rust anywhere on the car. I have taken pictures of all the typical areas that these cars will start to show corrosion (around the rear hatch wells, rocker panels, sun roof and door bottoms). The removeable sunroof does not leak, nor do any of the window seals or hatch. The car has not been driven much in the last 5 years, only to local car shows during the warm months. The whole exhaust system has been upgraded. The main & duals are made of 3" lightweight stainless, completely mandrel-bent. The catalytic converter is a free-flow style which provides less back pressure for the turbo/ exhaust. I had a Center Force Racing clutch and heavy-duty cable installed in 2005. I also installed an HKS Pro Flow air intake system but still have the original stock air cleaner assembly. There has been a manual boost control module also installed under the hood. Shown attached to the front of the radiator is an auxiliary fan to keep the radiator cool. Other than those modifications, the car is stock. I have had the aluminum rims refinished and spin-polished to a bright finish. There is no plastic clear coating on these rims which will fade and peel. The slots in the rims as well as the lug wells have been blacked out with a powder coat finish. These have always been the best looking SVO rims I have seen. The tires have tons of tread on them, but are starting to show their age (2001). The drivers seat is showing a tiny bit of wear along the upper/ outer seam. Otherwise the interior is in excellent shape. No cracks on the dashboard, or any wear on the carpets, interior panels or headliner. The shifter knob is worn, but I have a brand new one in the box that will go with the car. The leather steering wheel cover is worn, but has been protecting the original wrap quite well. The stereo is an Alpine CD player/ tuner which needs to be replaced (discs will not eject). I do have the original AM/FM cassette stock radio. There is a custom speaker box fitted into the rear hatch area which holds two 8" sub-woofers and two 6x9 speakers. The front dash speakers have also been upgraded with mid-range and tweeters. There are two power amplifiers mounted on the rear of the back seats. When the seats are folded back, the amplifiers are hidden. I have extra parts that will go with the car. My Dad worked for Borg Warner for a few years, so I took advantage and stocked-up on available parts. I have a brand new clutch (plate and rotor), four brand new brake rotors with four sets of pads, four brand new fuel injectors, four brand new coil springs and will even throw in two bottles of injection system cleaner. A custom car cover comes with, that's in good shape. I no longer have the time to pamper this car the way I used to. The car has always been respectfully driven and never beat on. It runs as strong as the day I bought it. If you would like any other specific pictures or details, do not hesitate to contact me. I have many more photos, but I can only upload 24. I will respond quickly. If you do not know too much about these cars but are interested, do a little research. These Mustangs were definitely a different breed. Fast, fun and race course ready! Great investment potential. Buyer will not be disappointed.

The item listed for auction is a 1984 Ford Mustang SVO. If you know your Mustangs then you know how rare this model really is. Here's a little history of this
model taken from Wikepedia:
Ford began to make a major push forward with the Mustang in 1982, nearly completely re-inventing every aspect of the vehicle, which included putting a new
emphasis on the model's sporty nature. Just prior to this, in the fall of 1981, Ford decided to form a division that could oversee both the company's racing
program and the production of limited-edition, high performance street legal vehicles based on or taking technology from the race vehicles. Officially, the division
was called the Special Vehicle Operations Department, but the public came to know them as simply SVO (S-V-O). Tasked with developing something that was
both plainly American and competent to compete with entry-level European sports cars of the day, the team went to work on the new Mustang, deeming that it
was the most obvious choice as a platform basis for a high-performance vehicle. Still ultimately concerned with issues such as fuel consumption and emissions,
SVO engineers opted to pass over the venerable Boss 302 in lieu of an updated, turbocharged, and stronger version of Ford's 2.3 liter inline four, originally used
in the Pinto. Endowing the engine with an advanced, computer controlled fuel injection system and an intercooled turbocharger system helped push power output
to 175 horsepower, fairly high for the time. With fine tuning and the addition of a new water-cooling system, power output rose to 200 horsepower (149 kW) for
1986 (205 horsepower (153 kW) for 439 85.5 SVOs) In addition, a "fuel grade" switch was added to the dash, allowing the driver to adjust the vehicle's
performance level depending on if premium or standard grade fuel was being used. The vehicle's standard 5-speed manual transmission was updated as well,
eventually receiving revised gearing and a factory installed Hurst shifter to improve feel and quickness. Also the 1986 SVO had different aero shaped headlights.
These headlights were designed for the 1984 model, but regulations would not allow them for another two years. One of the major downfalls to the turbocharged
inline four was the lack of torque in comparison to the V8, which, in the eyes of former muscle car owners, was considered a severe disadvantage. In addition to
the advanced engine, the SVO featured several key modifications over the standard Mustang to help increase performance. The front suspension geometry was
modified, f 15:1 ratio power-assisted rack-and-pinion steering system replaced the standard system, a limited slip, 3.45:1, 7.5" Traction-Lok axle was added for
the first year of production (later models used a 3.73:1 ratio, 7.5" axle), a new, ventilated four-wheel-disc braking system replaced the GT's disc/drum setup (a
first for the Fox platform), specially designed pedals were used to aid "heel-and-toe" shifting and a complete Koni suspension system featuring specially tuned
adjustable struts, shocks, and horizontal dampers replaced the setup used on the Mustang GT. Five-lug, 16 × 7 inch aluminum wheels wearing P225-50R16 VR
Goodyear Eagle "Gatorback" tires were standard as well (originally shod with German Goodyear NCT tires, and later Gatorbacks). The rear disc brakes, the five
lug hubs, the sixteen inch (406 mm) wheels, the quad-shock rear end, and the Konis were used on the SVO before any other Mustang. Interior features included
adjustable sport seats with lumbar supports, a leather-wrapped tilt steering wheel, shift lever, and emergency brake handle, power windows, door locks and A/C
and a premium stereo system, options that weren't normally found on small American coupes. However, an optional Competition Prep package deleted many of
those features to save weight. The exterior had a unique front grill that was only used on the SVO line, and a biplane spoiler that was also unique to the SVO.
The car was originally registered to the Ford Motor Company and used as a demo model in '84 and '85. It was taken to different dealerships around Wisconsin
and was purchased by a private owner in '86. I have documentation and the registration papers to verify this. It has the original owners and operator manuals.
This car has NOT been raced, abused or modified.
Drivetrain: It has the original 2.3 Liter intercooled turbo with factory Hurst 5 speed transmission. It starts and runs great. Can be driven anywhere. It has the usual
turbo smoke when you kick it down. Does burn a bit of oil. Still has factory Koni adjustable struts and shocks. Tires are in fair condition.
Body: The body is totally rust free from top to bottom. There is a little rust starting on the bottom of the doors. The body has a few minor dents, dings and
scratches but nothing major. It is missing the passenger side front marker light assembly. The paint is original and faded on the topside but could be buffed out.
Interior: Glass, carpet, door panels and center console in very good condition. Dashboard cover is cracked. Needs headliner. Leather on steering wheel and shift
knob are cracked. Passenger and rear seats are in good shape. Drivers seat, leather is cracked in a few spots. Does not have a stereo. A.C. worked but needs
line replaced.
Basically the car could be left as is and used as a daily driver or could be easily restored. I bought it with the intentions or restoring it but don't have the time or
cash to do the car justice. Hopefully the buyer knows what he's getting and can give this rare car the treatement it deserves. Feel free to contact me with any
questions or concerns. Buyer is responsible for all shipping or delivery costs.
I have more pics at http://s813.photobucket.com/albums/zz59/reaganbob2003/

Up for auction is probably one of the rarest and nicest ultra low mileage examples of a 1985.5 Ford Mustang SVO! I am listing this car for my boss and it is from his private collection which he has decided to reduce in size. I will describe the car and provide any and all details to give the prospective buyer peice of mind with his or her purchase.

First of all, this car is a 1985.5 Ford Mustang SVO which is a very low production car (approximately 475 in the world of this year). The 1985.5 model is also arguably the most desirable because of its 205 horsepower(the highest in the production run, flush mounted headlamps, dual exhaust, and ultra low production numbers. The car is black and has only 8,300 original miles! The carfax is clean and the pedigree I am about to describe is second to none-detailing this car's past all the way back to the original order sheet and dealer buyer's order in 1985! The car has always been in a climate controlled environment and is all original. We have the original sales order, buyer's order, window sticker, KONI gas strut adjustment knob tool and instruction manual in the plastic sleeve, four sets of original keys, original dealer key tags, original owner's manual, as well as assorted original owner's information pertaining to the purchase of this car back in 1985. One could spend over four hours just reading and enjoying this rare literature on the car which will be given to the new owner in a large folder.

The condition of this beautiful car is literally that of showroom status! In fact, it sits in our Ford showroom right now next to new Shelby mustangs and it fits right in! Starting with the black finish, the gloss of the paint is phoenominal with a deep shine. The panels all fit very nicely and the rear unique bi wing has no sag and is in great shape. All the wheels are in excellent shape as well as the body mouldings, side spats, and chrome pieces. The glass is all original and is free of scratches or chips. The factory dual exhaust out the back of the car is bright and beautiful. The car does not have a sunroof but does have the leather interior option. Moving to the interior, the original SVO leather is absolutely perfect with no tears, smells, stains or anything! The carpets, headliner, interior trim panels, dash, are all as close to brand new as a 8000 mile SVO from 1985.5 should be! The car smells new inside and the leather hurst shift boot, knob, and leather wrapped wheel are in beautiful shape. All options in the car work perfectly including nice cold A/C, premium sound system, hi low octane switches, power windows, locks, and all lighting systems. The car has the original fog lamp covers that also come with the car as well as the locking lug nut tool! There is so much that comes with this car, it truly is like buying it brand new back in 1985!

Under the hood is the 2.3 turbo engine in show condition. The pictures speak for themselves, but "clean under the hood" is not a phrase that does this engine bay justice as this is about as good as it gets and as close to new as it gets. The car has a battery tender installed for its indoor storage and that, as well as the cover will come with the car. The tender can easily be removed and does not compromise any of the original wiring under the hood. The oil has always been changed twice a year. My boss put motorcraft oil in the car and a motorcraft filter on the car. All the paint work on the flat black parts and the engine itself are ultra clean. Everything works perfectly under the hood and this car runs, drives, handles, like a brand new 1985.5 Ford Mustang SVO. There are no noted deficiencies in this car at all and everything on the car functions flawlessly.

The car was equipped in 1985.5 with a security code alarm system installed by the selling dealership(have original receipt). This is simply a small keypad affixed to the center console that can have a four digit code entered into it to disable the igntition. Evidently these were popular on eighties sports cars! The new buyer will get the code and original documentation. Also, the car was rust proofed by the original dealer as well(again we have the dealer work order) and the car has the little FORD plastic plugs in blue on the inner body panels, i.e. rocker panels etc. This was again done right at the original dealer back in 1985 and was paid for by the original owner. I cannot stress how clean the underneath of this car is and in fact you could eat off from it! The original dual exhaust is still shiny and there is absolutely no rust on this car anywhere! For safety reasons, the tires were recently changed to brand new Bridgestone Fusion Z rated tires which are like new. For safety reasons as well, because my Boss would drive this car occasionally( like twice a year!) the factory steering shaft with the old rag joint was replaced with a Maximum Motorsport double u joint steering shaft($300.00 value). The old shaft will come with the car, however as you may know, these old shafts were prone to the original rag joint failing and in a car this rare and beautiful, my Boss did not want to chance it when driving it the few times he did.

This car has been driven only 8300 miles over the last 27 years and lovingly maintained by its owners. It is probably one of the lowest mile examples on the planet and is sure to continue to go up in value. My boss does not need to sell this car and is not interested in low ball, unrealistic offers or conversations. I will accept phone calls and if you are serious or need any question answered I can put you in touch with him providing the question is of a relevant nature and you are indeed a serious buyer. This car, while in stunning shape, is being sold AS-IS with no warranty expressed or implied. Shipping and transportation is the buyer's responsibility. A $1000.00 dollar non refundable PAY PAL deposit is due within 24 hours of winning the auction. The remainder of the balance is due either in cash, or certified bank check, or wire within 72 hours after the auction is won. We have clear title in hand on the car which will be released to the new owner once above mentioned funds are verified as cleared. This car is for sale through our dealership and if it sells this auction can be ended at any time.

This is a real 1986 mustang SVO with 4690 original miles. I have all paperwork from the factory to the current day. All the owners can be contacted and i have spoken with them. The was was bought with 4467 miles. I drove it home and parked it. The SVO does go out on very short trips just to keep everthing lubed and running. I dont know where to start with the discription on the car. I will say the car is in showroom new condition. The undercarrage was hand waxed buy the second owner. Being that the car was never used the undercarrage has no rusted bolts or anthing it is like new. This is a blast to drive but looking at it all the time makes it a very expensive peace of garage funiture at the moment. ok there is a better idea of the car

The undercarrage.

All factory markings and stickers are still on the car.They look like new. There is no wear on the suspension and the floorpan still has a wonderful look to it. The car has never seen the rain and has always been covered. All the brackets and bushings are in new condition being they have all been lubed and are not dried out after 24 years. The exaust has never been touched and mosture has gotten into the mufflers and rotted them out. I due have replacements but have not installed them to to changing anthing on the car. All the mounts are in new condition and the underside is a perfect survivor and ready for the show ring.

The engine bay

The engine bay has never been detailed but maintained to a very high standard. NO ENGINE CLEANER HAS EVER BEEN USED just wd-40 to clean and lubercate all fittings, hoses mostureize the wiring and so forth. The engine runs great and does not smoke at all. There are no oil leaks and all fluids have been changed on a bi year bassis. Oil was chanded 3 monthe ago and was always serviced. The transmission, rear end have all had fluids changed. The brake system was serviced in september of 2011 with the front flex hoses replaced due to age and the complete system bleed. The SVO still has its factory pads and rotors wich are im perfect condition. The master cylinder is in perfect condition and does not need replacement.

The engine was a new timing belt and waterpump, which was replaced due to age not wear. The raditor was replaced and i have the original one which i was going to have fixed and reintalled. One of the fins started to leak and as you know you cannot get a factory replacement anymore. All the plated parts are in like new condition showing no wear. The engine compartment is in concourse condition. The A/C is still r-12 and does need a recharge. I have the r-12 which comes with the car. The a/c was working last summer but age got to it.

The Body

This SVO has never had any body or paint work. You can see this is a factory paint job showing all the faults of the erorr. The paint has a new luster and has never seen a buffer or the likes of. This car was always in a garage and covered so no uv light got to it. There are no door dings or anthing on the body again this is a true 4690 mile car. The paint has been waxed and that is all. There are no imperfections in the bumpercovers from parking at all. All the body panals fit as they left the factory are they good well they are factory. The paint has not even worn off the hood stops or the rear hatch from rubbing. The doors are a perfect factory fit and the hood has not shifted like all mustangs that have been used. The body is a perfect survivor and the paint is outstanding. A true mustang SVO fan would love this car due to the correctness of it

The interior

There is not to much to say it is a 4690 mile interior. The interior is perfect as it left the factory. Every part has its original sheen and look to it. The seats carpet, plastic panals are factory perfect. Several years ago the headliner was replaced due to the factory glue letting go and the original materal was used to replace it. The job was done to a very high level. There is no wear and the speedo was never disconnected if you due a vin search you will see the milage is correct. Everthing is working in the dash and all lighting is working. The leather shifter, shifter boot and handbrake lever are in prestine condition.

THE SEALS

All the seals and gaskets are still supple and due not leak. all the seals have been treated and are like new condition. Nobody has ever replaced them just taken care of.

The Paperwork

I have alot of paperwork which shows the millage to be true. The current title is from the state of florida and the MILAGE IS MARKED 4467 MILES 04/26/2011 ACTUAL. I have copies of the past title, window sticker, factory order sheet from the dealership to ford. I have all the glove box stuff including the dealer plastic keys. There is a binder of paperwork on the car. This is one of the nicest original SVO to be on the market and i think there are 3 others with lower miles out there. This SVO won the mustang nationals a while back.

This is a 300-mile, ALL ORIGINAL 1986 Ford Mustang SVO Turbo. The Ford Mustang SVO Turbo was the “top of the line” Mustang offered in 1986.
Powered by the Turbocharged 2.3 liter fuel injected 4 cylinder and 5 speed manual transmission, this Mustang was Ford Motor Company’s successful
attempt at creating an economical muscle car in the era following the times of the gas crisis. With 200hp and 240 lb-ft of torque, the SVO package also
includes a 15:1 ratio power assisted steering box, a 3.73:1 - 7.5” Traction-Lok axel, vented 4 wheel disc brakes, sport pedals, and a complete Koni
adjustable suspension package. The interior was also trimmed out in leather sports seats with lumbar supports, leather wrapped SVO tilt wheel, leather
shift knob and hand brake, power windows, A/C, and premium sound. The most noticeable touches to this car were the Bi-plane rear spoiler and raised
air dam in the hood.
This car is in absolutely immaculate condition! With only 300 miles, there is absolutely no rust, no paint, no stories other than being an amazing example
of a perfect like new Mustang. This SVO is also in the Ford Mustang SVO Registry, and features full documentation with many original pieces of
paperwork

For those of you unfamiliar with the Mustang SVO, they were very much ahead of their time and had many features which seperated them from the rest of the
mustang herd.. They feature a 2.3 Liter 4 cylinder engine with an advanced, computer controlled fuel injection system and an intercooled turbocharger system.
In addition, a "fuel grade" switch was added to the dash, allowing the driver to adjust the vehicle's performance level depending on if premium or standard grade
fuel is being used. The vehicle's standard 5-speed manual transmission was updated as well, receiving revised gearing and a factory installed Hurst shifter to
improve feel and quickness.
In addition to the advanced engine, the SVO features several key modifications over the standard Mustang to help increase performance. The front suspension
geometry was modified, a 15:1 ratio power-assisted rack-and-pinion steering system replaced the standard system, a limited slip, 3.45:1, 7.5" Traction-Lok axle
was added, a new, ventilated four-wheel-disc braking system replaced the GT's disc/drum setup (a first for the Fox platform), specially designed pedals were
used to aid "heel and toe" shifting and a complete Koni suspension system featuring specially tuned adjustable struts, shocks, and horizontal dampers replaced

After a second energy crisis, most people believed that V8-powered cars were living on borrowed time. Nevertheless, the public again began clamoring for performance cars. Enter the 1984-1986 MUSTANG SVO, a GT with a European approach to performance.

From Ford literature – “When Ford gave the slogan ‘The machine speaks for itself’ to the SVO, it knew the turbo four banger would be a sophisticated, race-proven automobile for driving enthusiasts. All of its exterior modifications, from the dual rear wing to the hood scoop are all functional. The power delivery is smoother with next to no turbo lag. This car offers world-class performance and can rival the cornering ability of the Ferrari 308 and Porsche 944.”

The Mustang SVO showed the world that with a sophisticated fuel injection system, turbo and intercooler, a 2.3 four-cylinder could make enough power to rival engines twice its size and still get 25 mpg.

2.3-Liter Turbo – Built a Ford’s Lima, Ohio plant, the 2.3 liter single overhead-cam four put out 205 bhp and 240 lb-ft for the 1986 models.

Five-Speed Transmission – Marketed as a serious driver’s car, the SVO was only available with a Borg-Warner T-5, 5-Speed, manual transmission and a Hurst short-throw shifter.
Suspension Upgrades – SVOs were upgraded with Koni adjustable gas pressurized shock absorbers, recalibrated coil springs, front and rear anti-roll bars and close-ratio power steering. This contributes to its outstanding handling.

Four-Wheel Discs – To ensure that SVO’s could stop as quickly as they accerlate, they were all equipped with four-wheel disc brakes. This didn’t become standard again on regular Mustangs until 1994.

Live Rear Axle – SVOs came with a 7.5-inch live rear axle with a Traction-Lok differential and quad rear shocks. 3.73 gears for the 1986 model.

Distinguishing Features – SVO variants can be distinguished from other ‘Stangs by twin square headlights, rear wheel spats, grill-less front styling, functional hood scoop, bi-level deck-lid spoiler and unique taillight treatment.

Driver-Oriented Interior – Interior equipment includes an 8,000 rpm tachometer, multi-adjustable sport bucket seats, leather-rimmed steering wheel, plus power door locks, mirrors and windows. Its pedals are configured to allow heel and toe downshifting.

Up for auction is one of the rarest of the "rare" Ford Mustang SVO's. This is the rarest year, in the rarest color and one of only 3 documented, surviving, Hertz Rent A Car SVO's that I know of. This is the only Hertz SVO restored to this level that I am aware of. There were about ten thousand SVO Mustangs produced over a three year period from 1984 to 1986. Of that number, only 37 of them were produced in this Dark Sage Green, paint code 4E. In 1985, Hertz purchased approximately 40 SVO Mustangs to be made available as rentals to their High Performance class customers. This car is truly a rare beauty.

In 1999, the car was restored to "Concours-Driven" condition, and remains in near-concours condition to this day. In April 2001, this car was featured in Mustang Monthly Magazine. The article documents some of the car's history and comments on how hard it was to restore a car of this vintage back then. Now, many of the NOS parts that were available then are simply, near-impossible to find. This car may be the only one of its kind, in this condition.

Over the years the car has aged gracefully. Some things that were incorrect in the car's original restoration have been made right, and the car runs as beautifully as it looks. I'd drive this car anywhere with full confidence! It's been garage kept since it's restoration in 1999, and continues to earn trophies wherever it goes. Not only does the car's condition deserve recognition, but its unusual color is a conversation starter even for those who don't know what the car is.

THIS IS A CAR I PURCHASED IN JUNE OF 05’ AND IS EXTREMELY CLEAN. IT SHOULD BE KEPT INSIDE AND ONLY DRIVEN ON NICE DAYS OR TO CAR SHOWS. THERE IS NO COMPARISON BETWEEN OTHER MUSTANG SVO CARS TO THIS ONE. THIS CAR IS IMMACULATE. SVO’S WERE MADE FOR ONLY 3 YEARS AND WERE WAY BEFORE THEIR TIME. IF YOU’VE NEVER DRIVEN ONE YOU WOULDN’T KNOW ABOUT ITS HANDLING, COMFORT, AND POWER.

THIS SVO IS CLASSIFIED BY FORD AS AN 85 ½ MODEL. THERE WERE ONLY 9844 CARS SOLD DURING ITS PRODUCTION YEARS. 4508 IN 1984, 1515 IN 1985, 439 IN 1985 ½ MODEL, AND 3382 CARS IN 1986 ITS LAST YEAR. I WAS TOLD BY THE PREVIOUS OWNER THAT THE VIN MADE THIS CAR NUMBER 438. I HAVE A CERTIFICATE THAT SHOWS IT WAS BUILT ON THE LAST DAY OF PRODUCTION. HE HAD OWNED THE CAR FOR 5 YEARS. SOME MAY WONDER WHY FORD PHASED THEM OUT BUT AT THAT TIME THE MUSTANG GT WAS SEVERAL THOUSANDS CHEAPER AND PEOPLE DIDN’T REALIZE AND WANT TO PAY FOR THE ADVANTAGES OF THE SVO VERSUS ITS SLOWER AND POORER HANDLING COUSIN THE GT. TECHNOLOGY COSTS MONEY. THE 84 AND 85 SVO’S HAD ABOUT 145 HP WHERE THE 85 ½ HAD 205 HP AND 86 WAS DROPED BACK TO 200HP WHICH MAKES IT REALLY QUICK AND FUN TO DRIVE

I HAVE THEN PUT IN LARGER FUEL INJECTORS AND FUEL PUMP, COLD AIR INDUCTION, A BOOST CONTROLLER TO TURN UP THE BOOST ON THE TURBO, A FRONT MOUNT INTERCOOLER FROM STINGER, A 3” DOWNPIPE FROM THE TURBO, A CUSTOM MANDREL BENT 2 ½” EXHAUST, AND A SPEC STAGE 1 CLUTCH. I HAVE NOT PUT THE CAR ON A DYNO, BUT BELIEVE WE ADDED AT LEAST 75 HP WITH THE UPGRADES.

THIS CAR IS IN SHOW CONDITION. I HAVE YET TO SEE AN SVO THAT WOULD COME CLOSE TO THE CONDITION OF THIS CAR. DON’T BE FOOLED BY THE OTHERS, AS THEY TEND TO BE FULL OF BODY DAMAGE, BAD PAINT, AND NOT-SO-GOOD INTERIOR. THIS CAR HAS BEEN TAKEN CARE OF.

THE EXTERIOR CONDITION IS EXCELLENT. IT HAS BEEN PAINTED ITS ORIGINAL COLOR 2R JALAPENO RED. IT IS A RUST FREE CAR AND HAS NEVER BEEN WRECKED. THE PASSENGER SIDE DOOR APPEARS TO HAVE A VERY SLIGHT PARKING LOT DOOR DING, BUT NO SCRATCH IN THE PAINT, SO NOT SURE WHAT HAPPENED. I BELIEVE THIS CAR HAS SPENT MOST OF ITS LIFE IN TEXAS. THE PAINT IS IN EXCELLENT CONDITION AND HAS NEW WEATHER STRIPS, HEADLIGHTS, PARKLIGHTS, TAILLIGHTS, AND HEADLINER. THE INTERIOR IS LIKE NEW. IT HAS WEAR ON THE LEATHER GEAR SHIFT KNOB DUE TO IT DRYING OUT. THE CAR HAS ICE COLD A/C WHICH HAS BEEN CONVERTED TO 134A.

I JUST PUT NEW RUBBER ON THE REAR OF THE CAR. I HAVE 3 OF THE GOODYEAR VR50 EAGLE BACKS WHICH WERE THE SAME SERIES TIRE WHICH IT ROLLED OFF THE SHOWROOM FLOOR WITH. I DO NOT HAVE A FOURTH TIRE BUT YOU COULD FIND ANOTHER IF YOU WANTED TO PUT THE ORIGINAL BRAND TIRES ON THE CAR. THESE TIRES ARE IN GREAT SHAPE.

A COUPLE OF MINOR PAINT STONE CHIPS ON THE FRONT AND THE SHIFTER KNOB AND THE DOOR DING ARE THE ONLY THINGS THAT I KNOW OF ON THE CAR THAT MIGHT NEED ATTENTION TO THE BEST OF MY KNOWLEDGE. THIS IS A VERY NICE CAR.

Here's a breakdown of what's been done to the car:

Complete Bottom End rebuild with all new parts/pistons/gaskets/seals etc. This work was done professionally by a well respected local engine builder who specializes in classic/race/muscle motors. Block was obviously magna-fluxed and checked without and issues found.

Complete Head rebuild and valve job, again with all new springs/valves/hydraulic lifters. This work was also performed by a local professional machine shop. Again, Head was checked for any warpage or flatness issues, none found.

Top and Bottom end were joined with a new Head Gasket.

The Turbo itself was again rebuilt at a local professional shop that specializes in rebuilding turbo units, shaft/impeller was checked without any issues and new bearings and fittings installed.

Intake Manifold (2 piece) was bolted to the engine again with new gaskets.

Radiator was flushed and pressure tested and new Radiator Cap installed.

The Overall Package: In addition to the advanced engine, the SVO featured several key modifications over the standard Mustang to help increase performance. The front suspension geometry was modified, 15:1 ratio power-assisted rack-and-pinion steering system replaced the standard system, a limited slip, 3.45:1, 7.5" Traction-Lok axle was added for the first year of production (later models used a 3.73:1 ratio, 7.5" axle), a new, ventilated four-wheel-disc braking system replaced the GT's disc/drum setup (a first for the Fox platform), specially designed pedals were used to aid "heel-and-toe" shifting and a complete Koni suspension system featuring specially tuned adjustable struts, shocks, and horizontal dampers replaced the setup used on the Mustang GT. Five-lug, 16 × 7 inch aluminum wheels wearing P225-50R16 VR Goodyear Eagle "Gatorback" tires were standard as well (originally shod with German Goodyear NCT tires, and later Gatorbacks). The rear disc brakes, the five lug hubs, the sixteen inch (406 mm) wheels, the quad-shock rear end (early 84 units used a solid steel traction bar with a rubber cover), and the Konis were used on the SVO before any other Mustang.Interior features included adjustable sport seats with lumbar supports, a leather-wrapped tilt steering wheel, shift lever, and emergency brake handle, power windows, door locks and A/C and a premium stereo system, options that weren't normally found on small American coupes. However, an optional Competition Prep package deleted many of those features to save weight. The exterior had a unique front grill that was only used on the SVO line, and a biplane spoiler that was also unique to the SVO. The Mustang SVO was the brainchild of the development team at Ford SVO (Special Vehicle Operations). While the SVO was only produced for 3 short years, it has been said "The SVO was the best handling Mustang produced". In 1986 3382 SVOs were built bringing the three year total to 9844 units.

This SVO was purchased new in Texas and driven daily until 1990 when the original owner decided to start a complete restoration due to the potential collectability of the SVO. At the time the car had some minor body damage to the lr quarter panel and front end however no structural damage, so it was decided to completely replace the entire front clip (hood, nosepiece, nosepiece reinforcement, and both fenders) as well as the lr quarter panel. All parts were professionally removed at the spot welds with no cutting and all new original Ford NOS sheet metal was purchased. The front clip was installed however the owner never got around to the rear quarter. The car has since been sitting in dry storage since 1990. This is a project car that someone with the ability and time can put back together and make a nice car of. All body parts are there to reassemble, he even purchased every support bracket and new inner and outer wheel houses new from Ford. The engine and trans are still in the car. Interior was removed and wrapped in plastic and comes with the car. The original 7.5 differential has been removed and replaced with a 2004 Mustang 8.8 with disc brakes. In addition there is an NOS 2.3 engine block still in the plastic, NOS headlights and side markers, 4 slightly used original Goodyear Gatorback tires, and many other miscellaneous SVO parts. This is a solid rust free car that I would hate to part out however I do not have the time to finish.
This car is under repair, hopefully on the road soon.

I got this car in early 2006 with the intention of gradually restoring it. I am pursuing a second college degree and don't have the resources to see that plan through now, so here it it is for sale. It is an early production "slapper bar"car built sometime prior to December 1983 when the traction bars were dropped in favor of quad shocks on the rear suspension.
First and foremost, it starts, runs, drives, and I have a clean title for it. It is one of about 9,800 SVOs ever built. It is on a current non-op registration, so there are no back fees stacking up. It will need to be smogged before you can get tags for it. Mileage is an estimate.

Engine:

Runs well, compression around 145-155psi on all cylinders, better performing E6SE turbo manifold and water cooled stock replacement T3 turbocharger. Exhaust was replaced at some point and I think the muffler is a Magnaflow or Dynomax. There is mild tone to the exhaust, but it is not loud at all. Valve seals have maybe 1000mi on them. The thermal fan switch does not work, so the fan doesn't come on. The fan controller is in fine shape and has never burned itself up nor the wiring. The A/C compressor was locked up when I bought the car and it still is, so the A/C doesn't work. The heater core leaks and has been bypassed; I have a new core that is included with sale of the car. A new timing belt and tensioner is also included. The battery is old and does not hold a charge for very long.

Body:

The paint is showing some age from desert sun exposure and could stand to be rubbed-out at the least. Some paint is cracking on the hood around the passenger headlight. Some urethane is showng through on the rear bumper cover. Some of the door trim is missing. Most of the paint has faded off of the mirrors. The tires are dry and cracked. The passenger rear is flat in the photos because the valve stem broke off while I was washing the car. I put another wheel on in the interim and the original is in the hatch. I just wanted to show that I have all four original wheels.

Interior:

Carpet has a spot here and there. The passenger front and rear bench seat is in pretty good shape. The driver's seat needs to be reupholstered. The dash pad has typical cracking, especially around the speaker grates. The fuzzy dash sections are in good shape. The steering wheel needs to be recovered. Plastic panels in the hatch are so-so and the hatch carpet is weak from sunlight. Spare tire is still present and good, although the tire iron and jack are missing.

I'm trying to be as complete as possible, but this is an old car, and I'm sure I'm missing something.

I am the original owner of this 1986 SVO. I drove it off the showroom floor from Young Ford in Charlotte. This car was a daily driver for about the first 10 years. Even after the SVO was replaced as my daily driver it was still driven 2 – 3K per year and sat covered in my garage during all that time. Needing new paint, some interior work and engine rebuild I started the process of restoration in 2009. BTW, this car has never been in any kind of accident.

Paint was done in 2009 back to original black and charcoal grey. Complete engine rebuild finished about 3,500 miles ago in 2012. Some of the engine mods include Boport racing cam, custom diamond pistons, manual boost controller, ported and polished head and manifold, larger valves, cold air intake, no cat, Dynomax super turbo mufflers, adjustable fuel pressure regulator, etc …

Still doing interior work but it’s in fairly good shape. Did a few pulls on the dyno after a 500 mile break in with RWHP at 248 and torque at 284. That was at 17 PSI of boost on 93 pump gas. Plenty of room to go up and I have tweaked the car more since those numbers were obtained. My biggest problem now is traction. Was thinking I wanted to go megasquirt and larger injectors but seeing how I have trouble keeping the tires hooked to the road in 1st through 2nd gears it seems rather pointless. What a fun car to drive and I have enjoyed it now for over 26 years.

Another first time entry found on ebay , it used to be a 1E but has had a repaint This 1984 Ford Mustang SVO, isn't exactly stock. Purists may not appreciate the subtle changes, but she will no longer be out-gunned by the many new turbocharged 4 cyclinders out there. Most changes: Recently built motor (less than 350 miles), with new pistons, rings, bearings, high flow oil pump, ported head w/oversized valves, ported intake-gutted top half, larger throttlebody, new/larger turbo, Bob's big log exhaust manifold, 3" exhaust from turbo (with high flow catalytic converter), custom highflow intercooler,engine shocks, stage 1 clutch/throw-out bearing, 55 lb injectors and Racetech fuel/ignition computer. Turbo control switch now controls an electronic adjustible boost controller. AFR guage is in place, so that you can be sure your ratio is good. Front-end has been lowered approx. 1 inch, with a new front-end alignment. Tires are in pretty good shape (Pep Boys). New brakes, rotors and calipers - front and rear. There are replacement (correct) brake light covers, and a new front-end header (she has had a couple of "taps"). Original intake, throttle body, exhaust manifold, intercooler, & correct size turbo could be available (negotiable). She could use some bodywork on the doors and roof, plus a new shot of paint (5 plus year old Maaco paint job currently-original color was light gray), as there is a little rust or paint bubble poking through in various places. Driver's door needs an adjustment. Undercarriage is sound, though. There is a spare rim, with a new tire mounted. Rims could use a freshening up. Interior head-liner is not stock material (but I have some). Sunroof is nice, but is aftermarket. Shocks and infamous lower control arms have been updated with Ebay found low mileage units. Driver side front seat is worn, passenger side is in great shape and rear is nice. There is a spare rear seat bottom available for material to fix the driver's seat. Hatch supports are tired and hold when they want. Carpet is in pretty good shape (but could use a cleaning). Vehicle mileage is approximate, as I may drive it around before the listing ends.

Previous owner's name was Cleighton Soares. He sold it to Dana Scott who registered it in his wife's name. Mr. Soares smacked up the front end and that is why he sold it. A replacement front clip was purchased from Paul Becker. The donor car for the front clip was an '84 SVO that ended up being sold to Roger K.(ninjaboy) as the basis of his White Trash SVO project. This '86 had the hilbilly mechanic treatment done to it before Dana bought it. Many of the underhood wiring connections were made with house wiring spec wire nuts. The air box was replaced with a K&N cone type(good) and the VAM was then loosely attached to the car with plumbers strapping(bad). The cam cover and various pieces under the hood were 'freshened up' with bright blue spray paint with little masking. The alternator had been replaced with a unit that only had a single v-bely pulley. The '86 leather seats were missing and some other seats installed instead, I think they were T-Bird seats. A monster tach had been installed, it was bolted thru the dash pad.

This is a very original SVO which had the same owner since 1992. The car does run and drive but has been sitting since the year 2000 so it will need some work to be considered a daily driver. I bought the car with the intention of restoring it but haven't had the time to devote to it. Here's some more detailed information. The car did not pass the strict California emissions test therefore the car cannot be sold to a resident of the state of California, NO EXCEPTIONS!. BIDDING IS OPEN ONLY TO NON-CALIFORNIA RESIDENTS.

Mechanical: As stated the car does run and drive. I have driven the car on a handfull of occassions and here is what I've observed. The engine starts easily and runs well. There is no smoking, knocking, overheating or odd noises. The car will occassionally hesitate on acceleration. I don't know if this is an issue with the turbo or something else. Turbo does kick in and work. The 5 speed trans will sometimes grind going into 2nd gear. If you don't shift too quickly it works fine. It will grind if you try to downshift into 2nd at a high speed. Transmission and clutch work fine other than the 2nd gear issue. Cooling fan doesn't seem to work. I never let the temp go higher than half way but the fan didn't come on at that point. Front end will need some attention. Noisy going over bumps. Brakes work fine. The tires look good but I'm sure they are quite old.

Exterior: The body and paint look good. There are no dents or rust on the body. The paint on the front bumper is scraped. The winshield has a large crack and will need to be replaced.

Interior: Interior is pretty nice for the age. Seats are good shape with no tears. Dash is solid with no cracks. The car has a sunroof which leaks and has damaged the front section of the headliner. Overall a nice interior.

THIS IS A TRUE 1985 1/2 FORD MUSTANG SVO AND ONLY 439 OF THEM WERE PRODUCED! I purchased the car in 2005 from a young engineer at Ford who had bought the car in 1994 from Arizona where it originally came from according to the window sticker. He then registered the car in Michigan (this is where his parents lived). Over the next 11 years he spent over $11,000.00 on NOS parts and restoration of the exterior, body and braking system of the car and only drove the car about 1000 miles. The car has been restored on the outside and is a 10 out of a 10. Every molding and light have been replaced on the car with NOS parts. The body had no rust to start with, the underside of the car has very minor rust staining on some of the seams. The interior of the car is a 9 1/2 out of a 10. Who ever buys this car - if you want it to be a complete restoration, all you will need to buy is a NOS shifter knob which will run around $200.00 on E-Bay. The engine runs good, the clutch is new and I just replaced the battery with a new one. The car does have the proper Good year Gator Back size and style tires which are impossible to get anymore - they are brand new and have not seen the road. The car also still has the Koni shocks on it. This car just needs the engine and engine compartment detailed to make it a complete restoration. The documentation that will come with the car consists of the original window sticker, the build sheet and the owners manual as well as some receipts for miscellaneous parts that the previous owner bought. This car is perfect for the person who wants to do an SVO restoration but does not want to go throught the aggrevation of dealing with the body work or getting the NOS parts (which are expensive and almost impossible to get). The reason I am selling this car is so that I can concentrate on the restoration of the 46 mile 1986 SVO that I bought (see Mustang Monthly Magazine September 2006 - "The car that doesn't exist").
